{{Infobox Non-profit | Non-profit_name = Ubuntu Foundation | Non-profit_logo = | Non-profit_type = | founded_date = {{start date|2005|07|01}}<ref name="mailingListAnnounce" /> | founder = [[Mark Shuttleworth]] and [[Canonical Ltd.]]<ref name="mailingListAnnounce" /> | location = <!-- this parameter modifies "Headquarters" --> | origins = | key_people = Mark Shuttleworth, Benjamin Mako Hill, Colin Watson, James Troup<ref name="mailingListAnnounce" /> | area_served = | product = | focus = | method = | revenue = | endowment = | num_volunteers = | num_employees = | num_members = | subsid = | owner = | Non-profit_slogan = | homepage = | dissolved = | footnotes = }} The '''Ubuntu Foundation''' is a [[purpose trust]] founded by [[Mark Shuttleworth]] and [[Canonical Ltd.]] to ensure the long-term maintenance of the [[Ubuntu (operating system)|Ubuntu]] [[Linux distribution]] independently of the commercial activities of Canonical Ltd. Its initial funding commitment is $10M.<ref name="mailingListAnnounce">{{cite mailing list |url=https://lists.ubuntu.com/archives/ubuntu-announce/2005-July/000025.html |title=Announcing Launch of ($10m) Ubuntu Foundation |mailinglist=ubuntu-announce |last=Hill |first=Benjamin Mako |accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref><ref name="blogPost">{{cite web |url=http://www.ubuntu.com/news/UbuntuFoundation |title=New Ubuntu Foundation Announced |accessdate=August 31, 2010 |publisher=Canonical Ltd.}}</ref>
Its current [[advisory board]] is made up of [[chairman]] Mark Shuttleworth, founder of Canonical Ltd., and representatives of the Ubuntu Community Council and the Ubuntu Technical Board.<ref name="mailingListAnnounce" /><ref name="blogPost" />
Although it was originally announced that the Ubuntu Foundation would employ core members of the Ubuntu community<ref name="blogPost" /> as of 2008, the Foundation remains dormant. Mark Shuttleworth describes it as an "emergency fund" in the event that Canonical's involvement in the Ubuntu project ends.
